limb","Complete excretion of filtered load","Passive reabsorption in the collecting duct enhanced by antidiuretic hormone","Active transport against concentration gradient in descending limb"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Epassive reabsorption in the collecting duct is enhanced by antidiuretic hormone\u003C/strong\u003E. Urea is freely filtered at the glomerulus and approximately 50% is passively reabsorbed in the proximal tubule. In the presence of antidiuretic hormone, urea transporters in the collecting duct facilitate passive reabsorption of urea, which helps maintain the medullary concentration gradient necessary for water reabsorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive secretion throughout the proximal tubule\u003C/strong\u003E - Urea reabsorption in the proximal tubule occurs through passive mechanisms rather than active secretion.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive reabsorption in the ascending limb\u003C/strong\u003E - The ascending limb has low permeability to urea and does not actively reabsorb it.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete excretion of filtered load\u003C/strong\u003E - Only 30-50% of the filtered urea load is typically excreted in the final urine.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport against concentration gradient in descending limb\u003C/strong\u003E - Urea movement in the descending limb follows passive concentration gradients rather than active transport mechanisms.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe recycling of urea between the collecting duct and medullary interstitium contributes to the high osmotic gradient in the medulla, which is essential for the kidney\u0027s ability to concentrate urine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Urea is freely filtered at the glomerulus and undergoes both secretion and reabsorption in the nephron.","Urea reabsorption in the collecting duct is enhanced by antidiuretic hormone, helping to maintain medullary concentration gradient.","The concentration of urea in the medullary interstitium is important for the kidney\u0027s ability to concentrate urine."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57440"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17671"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57440"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T20:49:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T20:50:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10385"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71970"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","nam